hing other than bags, this has always seemed to me to be something of a miracle.  Anyway, here's how we do it.  <br>
<br>
1. pour some boiling water into the pot to heat it up, then dump it out.<br>
<br>
2. put in the tea leaves.<br>
<br>
3. IMMEDIATELY pour in boiling or just-was-boiling water.<br>
<br>
4. wait a minute.<br>
<br>
5. shake madly before serving (just kidding).<br>
<br>
So, is this the way tea is made everywhere else in the world?  It really works until you hit the bottom of the pot.  Oh, and the aesthetics are kind of ruined (at my grandparents') because in addition to the beautiful pot with the tea, they also bring out the kettle, which is ugly beaten metal, and use it to thin the tea out when you're down near the bottom of the pot.<br>
<br>
Chris<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :hat --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/pimp.gif ALT=":hat"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eirikraude>Eirik Raude</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/4/03 4:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Just a tip</span><hr size=1> I've recently discovered a &quot;new&quot; way of making tea. I use one of these:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.pvv.ntnu.no/~erikboge/kaffe/bilder/bistro.jpg">www.pvv.ntnu.no/~erikboge...bistro.jpg</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
...which are usuallu intended for coffeemaking (like in this picture). But which work great for tea as well. Gives you all the benefits of using &quot;real&quot; tea while sparing your mouth a flood of dried leaves.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
My current favorite is russian tea, by the way, which is basically hellish strong black tea. Needs some sugar though, or the bitterness will overwhelm you... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=backwards7>backwards7</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/4/03 2:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Chai</span><hr size=1> Recently I turned thirty and I've been through that minor midlife crisis where you desperately attempt to listen to all the records that defined your youth, and mope around thinking about old girlfriends that you could have, and probably should have, settled down with. I've also been thinking about all the places I've been in the world, because I did a hell of a lot of travelling in my mid/late 20s.<br>
<br>
I got very nostalgic for the Chai that I used to buy from street vendors in India. It's a tea made with condensed milk and spices and it's incredibly sweet.<br>
<br>
Drinking Chai is a very important social ritual in India because it gives you the opportunity to network with other travellers. It doesn't cost much to buy someone a glass of Chai and India is one of those places where you really need to talk with other backpackers, just so you get an idea of what to expect further down the road. It's such a Darwinian country - it's very easy to lose the shirt off your back if you hesitate or show any signs of naivety, so forewarned is forearmed.<br>
<br>
There's a bench seat outside the Navrang hotel, in the Main Bazaar area of New Delhi, where westerners gather and drink Chai. Nearby is an electrical junction box, attached to a pole, that sits in a depression in the road. Often this depression will fill up with water.<br>
<br>
One night I was wrapped up in a couple of blankets, drinking Chai outside the Navrang. You end up participating in several different conversations all at once - A Frenchmen called Reynard was explaining to me how he made a living stealing from other travellers. Some guy from Newcastle was telling me about the time he got stranded in the no-man's land between the Greek and Yugoslavian borders. Neither country would let him in because he had no money. A big group of Northern lads were bragging about the fights they'd been in and I was horrified that everyone, bar myself, was able to press their nose flat against their face. One man had just returned from one of the big wildlife reserves where he'd seen a tiger unsuccessfully try to kill an elephant.<br>
<br>
If you buy Chai on the trains it comes in tiny clay cups. Whenever a train stops, or slows down to a walking pace, tea vendors will jump on board, with their kettles, and attempt to sell you Chai, even if it's 3 in the morning. After you've finished you can throw the clay cups out of the train window where they shatter harmlessly on the tracks. In some parts of India they've begun to use small plastic cups - a big mistake. You're going to see these blowing about everywhere.<br>
<br>
I found a recipe for Chai on the internet and, last week, I decided that I was going to make some to see if I could recapture the taste of the Chai that I used to drink in India.<br>
<br>
First of all I had to trek up to Westcliff to retrieve my spices, which are currently housed in a pair of plastic Tupperware boxes in a friend's garage. I spent the afternoon measuring out Ground Cloves, Allspice, Black pepper and Cinnamon; pounding Cardamom pods with a pestle; and blending the small pile of spices with condensed milk. The recipe I used recommends using unsweetened milk but really you do need to use the sweetened variety.<br>
<br>
To make the Chai, you spoon some of this mixture into a mug of ordinary black tea. The concoction actually gains in flavour by the day, because the spices infuse into the condensed milk. <br>
<br>
I'd forgotten how sweet Indian Chai can be - You don't really need a mug of it - a small coffee cup is enough. I think to get the really authentic taste, the Chai needs to be brewed in a filthy kettle next to an open sewer, but the stuff I made was a fair approximation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/5/03 9:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Pickle Tea</span><hr size=1> My tea stories are unfortunately quite mundane and regrettably commercial.<br>
<br>
Back in 1995, the girl I was dating introduced me to one of the Celestial Seasonings herbal tea brands called Sleepytime. (I warned you.)  She liked to take it with a bit of brown sugar and milk.  I recall having some and thinking it tasted a bit like dill pickle, thus its nickname henceforth by me, &quot;pickle tea.&quot;<br>
<br>
If you've had this before, all I can do is apologize for my taste buds, since I seem to be the only person who's made the association between chamomile flowers, spearmint leaves, lemon grass, tilia flowers, blackberry leaves, orange blossoms, hawthorn berries, rosebuds...and pickles.<br>
<br>
It continues to be my non-alcoholic nightcap. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A> at: 10/5/03 9:50 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=papercutfun@lucifer>Papercut Fun</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/6/03 6:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Teabags</span><hr size=1> I'm glad my online petition worked!  Thanks Mike.<br>
