<br>
As some of you know, I went to Beijing before I came home to Australia. Beijing is a remarkable place, very different from Hong Kong. The people there are imperial - they know their long long history, and know in their hearts that Beijing is the centre of the world. Its surprisingly clean (I had been told it was the most polluted place in the world outside of Mexico City, but I think this was limited ot the air pollution index), is very safe (there are soldiers and police everywhere) and has plenty to see. I went to the Great Wall, the Forbidden City, and eyed off Mao's Tomb (couldn't be bothered lining up to get in, though), It was the week before National Day, and the place had a festive ambience.<br>
<br>
I met two girls in Tiannamen Square, who befriended me - I figure they wanted to practice their English. We went wandering about the hotungs of Beijing - the old housing, some of it dated back for centuries. The government is gradually pulling it down and replacing it with low cost cruddy housing. One of the girls asked me if I wanted to drink some tea. I was quite enthused about this, knowing I had a readymade audience amongst you all for what would otherwise be a disinteresting tale.<br>
<br>
We went into a place which sold tea. There was an odd shaped wooden table carved from the root of a tree and polished and lacquered it up. The woman serving us tea placed three thimble sized cups in front of us. She poured us ginseng oolong tea, which was quite amazing, because by the third cup it had become sweet. I ended up buying some of this. We also had some sturdy green tea, made with the leaves still on the twigs. <br>
<br>
My Hong Kong and Japanese manners - picking up the cup with both hands, tapping with my forefinger on the table by the side of the cup to say thank you, not letting someone pour themselves, and handing over my money with both hands - had the locals amazed, because they are not that polite themselves, but could recognise it.<br>
<br>
I kept my eyes open for the Silk Man, but I think he was out of town.<br>
<br>
I ended up sending from Hong Kong my oolong tea to one of the girls I met because Australia has such a strict policy on bringing foodstuffs into the country, that I would have had to have surrended it at customs.<br>
<br>
